answers.body_markdown:
&gt; How can I refactor this Class in Java?

As Federico commented, for a program this small it is neither necessary or advisable to do this.  It is so small that splitting out parts of the code will not improve readability.

However, doing it *for the purpose of learning to program in Java* is not a bad thing.  So lets assume that *that* is your goal.

&gt; I originally tried to use OOP and add the `Scanner` in it&#39;s own class but I struggled to get the input from the scanner in the main method, when the `Scanner` was in a different class.

Well, we would need to see what you did to understand your difficulty.

If the input requirements were complex, factoring them into a separate class (or even methods) might work.  But if you attempt it here, you end up adding many lines of code for no benefit.  

Using OOP is not a *goal* in its own right.  It is a technique that you use to achieve other goals.  However, *learning to use* OOP is a goal.

&gt; Ideally I would have also wanted to add the for loop in a separate method to clean up the code, but I wasn&#39;t able to access the `websites.length` field when I added it in a separate class.

You wouldn&#39;t put it in a separate class!  Put it in a separate method of your `Search` class. 

The problem you most likely encountered is that `website` was out of scope because it was declared as a local variable within the `main` method.  To make `website` accessible in another method it either needs to be declared as a field, or you need to pass it as a parameter to the method.  Here is an *illustrative* example of the first way:


    public class Search {
    
        private static String[] websites = {
            &quot;Google&quot;, &quot;http://www.google.com&quot;, 
            &quot;Facebook&quot;, &quot;http://www.facebook.com&quot;, 
            &quot;Ebay&quot;, &quot;http://www.ebay.com&quot;, 
            &quot;Netflix&quot;, &quot;http://www.netflix.com&quot;
        };
    
        public static void main(String[] args) {    
            System.out.println(&quot;Enter Your Search Query&quot;);
            Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);
            String userInput = sc.nextLine();
            search(userInput);
        }
       
        private static void search(String userInput) {
            for (int i = 0; i &lt; websites.length; i++) {
                if (userInput.equals(websites[i])) {
                    System.out.println(&quot;We Found The Value&quot;);
                    System.out.println(websites[i]);
                    System.out.println(websites[i + 1]);
                    break;
                } else {
                    System.out.println(&quot;There is no matching file&quot;);
                }
            }
        }
    }

The above is not a good example of a *useful* refactoring.  And it is not OO ... because we are using `static` methods and `static` fields.  But it illustrates how you can share things between different methods (and even classes) by using fields.

And ... once again ... OO is not a goal in its own right.  So the above is sufficient to meet your functional requirements.  But if you wanted to make the above more OO you *could*:

  1.  Make the `search` method an instance method by removing the `static`.
  2.  Call it like this:

          Search s = new Search();
          s.search(userInput);

(Making `websites` an instance field would probably be counter-productive.  If your requirements call for the searcher to check against a fixed set of websites, using a `static` for that is a natural way to do it.)

---------------------------

&gt; I would appreciate any help or ideas on how I could refactor this simple lines of code to improve performance or in line with Java best practices.

First of all &quot;best practice&quot; is an *unhelpful* term in the context of programming / software engineering.  Please read [No Best Practices!](https://www.satisfice.com/blog/archives/5164) to understand what I mean.

Second, there is nothing you can do to improve performance for this code in any *significant* way.  Starting up a Java JVM and loading your code will take 100s of milliseconds.  Waiting the the user&#39;s input will take seconds.  But the time to do the actual searching will be a couple of **microseconds**.  Your code&#39;s performance is irrelevant, in this example.

Now you could make the code simpler and more readable by doing either of the following:

  - Change `websites` into 2 arrays, one containing the website names, and the other the corresponding URLs.  (Mixing the search keys and search values into one array leads to problems.)
  - Change `websites` into `HashMap&lt;String, String&gt;` and you can then replace the loop with a `get` call.

But the flipside is that both of those will make initializing the `websites` more complicated.  (In a real application, would be loading that information from a configuration file, or searching a database ...)

Also, as noted in the comments, you could separate the functionality of searching from printing the results.  Read about the [Separation of Concerns][1] design principle.


  [1]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Separation_of_concerns

